-- Lead Is Biggest Decliner as Cotton Gains: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C l a u d i a   C a r p e n t e r
-- 2013-04-02T16:07:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-02/lead-is-biggest-decliner-as-cotton-gains-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI gauge of
24 commodities declined 0.4 percent to 650.36 by 5:01 p.m. in
London. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials was
down 0.9 percent at 1,522.981.  BASE METALS  Copper futures fell for a third straight session in New
York as record unemployment in Europe added to concern that
demand will weaken, amid signs of slowing growth in  China  and
rising stockpiles of the metal. Lead slumped 2.5 percent.  Copper futures for delivery in May slid 0.3 percent to
$3.3645 a pound on the Comex in New York. Yesterday, prices
touched the lowest since Aug. 3.  On the LME, copper for delivery in three months dropped 1.2
percent to $7,449 a ton ($3.38 a pound). The bourse was shut
yesterday and March 29 for public holidays.  Base metals markets: NI BMMKTS  SOFT COMMODITIES  Coffee futures fell on signs of abundant global supplies.
Cotton advanced 1.6 percent.  Arabica-coffee futures for May delivery dropped 0.7 percent
to $1.374 a pound on ICE Futures U.S. in New York. Earlier, the
price slumped as much as 1.8 percent.  Vietnam  is the second-
biggest producer. A bag weighs 60 kilograms (132 pounds).  Raw-sugar futures for May delivery fell 0.7 percent to
17.57 cents a pound on ICE. Earlier, the price touched 17.5
cents, the lowest since July 21, 2010.  Cocoa futures for May delivery dropped 0.2 percent to
$2,180 a metric ton. The price climbed in the previous four
sessions.  Cotton futures for May delivery jumped 1.9 percent to 89.02
cents a pound, heading for the biggest gain since March 14.  Orange-juice futures for May delivery climbed 0.7 percent
to $1.349 a pound.  Soft commodities markets: NI SOMKTS  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures extended a rally to the highest price since
July on speculation that consumers will boost purchases of
cheaper U.S. pork as an alternative to more-expensive meats.
Cattle were little changed.  Hog futures for June settlement rose 0.7 percent to 92.225
cents a pound at 9:38 a.m. on the  Chicago  Mercantile Exchange,
after reaching 92.45 cents, the highest for a most-active
contract since July 9. Prices are up 4.5 percent since March 19.  Cattle futures for June delivery fell less than 0.1 percent
to $1.2405 a pound in Chicago, after fluctuating between gains
and losses. The commodity lost 6.2 percent this year through
yesterday.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement declined 0.2
percent to $1.474 a pound. Prices were down 4.3 percent this
year through yesterday.  Livestock markets: NI LVMKTS  CRUDE OIL  West Texas Intermediate oil fell for
a second day on speculation a report will show that U.S. crude
supplies rose to the highest level in more than 22 years.  WTI oil for May delivery dropped 64 cents, or 0.7 percent,
to $96.43 a barrel at 11:18 a.m. on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The contract touched $97.80 yesterday, the highest
intraday price since Feb. 13. The volume of all futures traded
was 3 percent below the 100-day average for the time of day.  Brent for May settlement decreased 35 cents, or 0.3
percent, to $110.73 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures
 Europe  exchange. The volume of all futures traded was 6.9
percent higher than the 100-day average.  Oil markets: NI OILMARKET  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Corn for May delivery dropped 0.9 percent to $6.3675 a
bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade. Futures tumbled into a
bear market yesterday, dropping 13 percent in two days and
falling 23 percent from last year’s closing high in August.  Wheat for May delivery rose 0.3 percent to $6.6625 a bushel
in Chicago, while soybeans for delivery in the same month gained  percent to $13.9225 a bushel.
Grains markets: NI GRMKTS  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold declined the most in a month as physical demand ebbed
and a stronger dollar trimmed demand for the precious metal as
an alternative investment.  In New York, gold futures for June delivery fell 1.1
percent to $1,583.80 an ounce on the Comex, heading for the
biggest drop since Feb. 28.  Silver futures for May delivery retreated 1.4 percent to
$27.55 an ounce in New York, after reaching $27.425, the lowest
since Aug. 3. It closed at $27.944 yesterday, a 20 percent drop
from an Oct. 4 high, meeting the common definition of a bear
market.  Precious metal markets: NI PCMKTS  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline fell a third consecutive day as refinery
maintenance lessened.  Gasoline for May delivery fell 4.75 cents, or 1.5 percent,
to $3.0542 a gallon at 10:05 a.m. on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. Trading volume on the Nymex was 109 percent above the
100-day average.  Gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide, rose 0.3 cent to
$3.637 a gallon, AAA said today on its website. Prices are 28.8
cents below a year earlier after falling in March for the first
time in 10 years, according to AAA data.  Oil Products Europe: NI OPEMKT Gasoline: NI GASOLINE Heating
oil: NI HEATOIL  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures dropped for a third day in New York as
forecasts showed that chilly weather in the eastern U.S. this
week will give way to rising temperatures.  Natural gas for May delivery retreated 4 cents, or 1
percent, to $3.975 per million British thermal units at 10:50
a.m. on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Trading was 30 percent
above the 100-day average for the time of day. Prices have risen
19 percent this year.  U.K. natural gas: NI NUKMKT Gas market: NI GASMARKET Americas
natural gas: NI AGASMARKET European natural gas: NI EGASMARKET  European Carbon Permits  European Union emission permits gained 2.1 percent to 4.91
euros a metric ton.  EU Carbon Emissions: NI ECBMKT  To contact the reporter on this story:
